<hr />
<dl style="margin-left: 2 em">
  <a name="obliquedisplaydesign"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OBLIQUE DISPLAY DESIGN (or FLAG)</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf2.html#flagforslanteddisplay">flag for slanted display</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1307.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1307.gif" alt="[Pont-&agrave;-Celles]" border="0" height="141" width="147"></a><br />
  <em>Flag of the Army For Slanted Display, Bolivia (fotw & CS)</em> 
  </dd>
  
  <hr />
  <a name="obverse"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OBVERSE </dt>
  <dd>The face, or more important side, of a flag; and in the Western tradition 
  always depicted with the hoist to the observer&rsquo;s left - the dexter in heraldry &ndash; see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd1.html#dexterhoist">dexter hoist</a>&rsquo; (also
  '<a href="vxt-dvd4.html#double-sided">double-sided 1)</a>', 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm3.html#mirrorimage">mirror image</a>&rsquo;, and 
  '<a href="vxt-dvt6.html#two-sided">two-sided 1)</a>'.
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d1453.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1453.gif" alt="Portuguese flag - obverse" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2227.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2227.gif" alt="St Kitts and Nevins flag - obverse" border="0" height="108" /></a> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3349.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3349.gif" alt="Guinea flag - obverse" border="0" height="108" /></a><br /><em>Obverses: National Flags of <a href="pt.html">Portugal</a>,
  <a href="kn.html">St Kitts and Nevis</a> and <a href="gn.html">Guinea</a> (fotw)</em>
  	<p><em>Please note however, that in Arabic tradition the 
  flag is generally depicted with the hoist to the observer&rsquo;s right &ndash; the sinister 
  in heraldry (see also &lsquo;</em><a href="vxt-dvs4.html#sinister"><em>sinister</em></a><em>&rsquo;; 
  &lsquo;</em><a href="vxt-dvd1.html#dexter"><em>dexter</em></a><em>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;</em><a href="vxt-dvr2.html#reverse"><em>reverse</em></a><em>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;</em><a href="vxt-dvs4.html#sinister"><em>sinister hoist</em></a><em>&rsquo;). </em> 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2900.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2900.gif" alt="Saudi Arabian flag - obverse" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br><em>National Flag of <a href="sa.html">Saudi Arabia</a> (fotw)</em> </dd>
  
  <hr />
  <a name="occasionalflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OCCASION FLAG</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc6.html#commerorativeflag">commemorative flag</a>&rsquo;.
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d1269.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1269.gif" alt="commemorative flag" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em><a href="ca_ab100.html">Centennial Flag</a> 1905-2005 Alberta, Canada (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr />
  <a name="occitancross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OCCITAN CROSS</dt>
  <dd>A variation of the cross clechee which has a voided twelve-pointed gold cross, with a gold roundel placed at each of those points - a Cross of Toulouse (see also 
  �<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#cross">cross 2)</a>�, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#crossclechee">cross clechee</a>&rsquo;, 
  �<a href="vxt-dvcs.html#crossofpisa">cross of Pisa</a>�, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr4.html#roundel">roundel 2)</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvv2.html#voided">voided</a>&rsquo;).
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d3069.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3069.gif" alt="Occitan cross" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4819.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4819.gif" alt="Occitan cross" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3070.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3070.gif" alt="Occitan cross" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>Flag of <a href="fr-lr.html">Languedoc</a>, France (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="eu-occit.html">Occitania</a> (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="es-l-vda.html">Val d'Ar�n</a>, Spain (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr />
  <a name="ocila"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OCILA</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf1.html#firesteel">firesteel</a>&rsquo;.
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d2258.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2258.gif" alt="ocila" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>Flag of <a href="rs-bg-zv.html">Zvezdara</a>, Serbia (fotw) </em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="offcentered"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OFF-CENTRED</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="#offcenteredcross">off-centred cross 2)</a>&rsquo; and 
  �<a href="#offcenteredcross">off-centred cross 3)</a>� 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc2.html#centered">centred</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="#offset">off-set towards</a>&rsquo;). <br>
  </dd>

  <hr /><a name="offcenteredcross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OFF-CENTRED CROSS</dt>
  <dd>1) Generically see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs1.html#scandinaviancross">Scandinavian Cross</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  <dd>2) Specifically, a cross of the Scandinavian-type that is used on a flag 
  which is not from, or has no connection with, that region &ndash; a horizontal Latin or Scandinavian-type cross.</dd> 
  <dd>3) A cross whose vertical 
  arm may or may not be centred but whose 
  horizontal arm is closer to the top or bottom of the flag &ndash; but see note below.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4456.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4456.gif" alt="Denmark" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d619a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d619a.gif" alt="Volyinia, Ukraine" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d619b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d619b.gif" alt="Thunstetten, Switzerland" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br />
  <em>National Flag of <a href="dk.html">Denmark</a> (fotw); 
  Flag of 
  </em> 
  <a href="ua-lc.html"><em>Volyinia</em></a><em>, Ukraine (fotw); Flag of </em> <a href="ch-be034.html">
  <em>Thunstetten</em></a><em>, Switzerland (fotw)</em><p>
    <em>Please note with regard to 3) that in heraldic terms an off-centred cross 
  whose vertical arm is centred but whose horizontal arm is closer to the top of 
  a flag may be blazoned a Latin cross throughout, or if closer to the bottom of the flag a Latin cross throughout reversed &ndash; see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#latincross">Latin Cross</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr2.html#reversed">reversed 2)</a>&rsquo; 
	and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt1.html#throughout">throughout</a>&rsquo;).</em> </dd>
  <hr /><a name="offset"></a><a name="offsettowards"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OFF-SET (or OFFSET) TOWARDS</dt>
  <dd>The term used to describe a charge (or charges) or a stripe (or stripes) that is (or are) set 
  towards the hoist, fly, top or base of a flag, rather than lying on its vertical or horizontal meridian 
   &ndash; shifted towards or shifted to but see note b) below (also) &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc2.html#centered">centred</a>&rsquo;, 
  �<a href="vxt-dvch.html#charge">charge</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi4.html#inset">inset</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm2.html#meridian">meridian</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="#offcentered">off-centred</a>&rsquo; and
  &lsquo;<a href="#opticalproportions">optical proportions</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d714.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d714.gif" alt="Ensign - Israel" border="0" width="158" height="105"></a>
<a href="../images/v/vxt-d714a.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d714a.gif" alt="Cape Verde Islands" border="0" width="179" height="105"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2321.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d2321.gif" alt="Liechtenstein" border="0" width="179" height="105"></a>
  <br /><em><a href="il~civil.html">Civil Ensign of Israel</a> (fotw); National Flag of the 
  <a href="cv.html">Cape Verde Islands</a> (fotw); National Flag of 
  <a href="li.html">Liechtenstein</a> (fotw) </em>
  <p><em>Notes<br>
a) These terms should always be accompanied by a further description, for example, off-set towards the hoist.<br>
b) The term �shifted to� (although much used) is potentially inaccurate in that it implies a position against the edge of a flag, so the Editors suggest that one the alternatives (as given herein) are to be preferred in description.
</em></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="officersbroadpennant"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OFFICER&rsquo;S BROAD PENNANT (or PENDANT)</dt>
  <dd>See <a href="vxt-dvb7.html#broadpennant">broad pennant 3)</a> and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-o.html#officerspennant">officer's pennants</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1246.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1246.gif" alt="[yacht commodore]" border="0" width="186" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em><a href="fi-jakt.html#com">Yacht Club Commodore&rsquo;s Broad Pennant</a>, Finland (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
    <hr /><a name="officersflags"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OFFICER&rsquo;S FLAGS</dt>
  <dd>In US usage and in some others, those flags that are flown by the past and present 
  officers of a club, especially of a yacht or boating club &ndash; yacht officers flags
  � but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb7.html#broadpennant">broad pennant 3)</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-o.html#officerspennant">officer's pennants</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d574.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d574.gif" alt="[yacht commodore]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d574a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d574a.gif" alt="[yacht vice commodore]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d574b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d574b.gif" alt="[yacht rear commodore]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <span class="style2"><em>Typical examples: 
  <a href="us~ytof.html#ycom">Yacht Commodore</a>, <a href="us~ytof.html#yvcom">Yacht Vice Commodore</a> 
  and <a href="us~ytof.html#yrcom">Yacht Rear Commodore</a>, US (fotw)</dd></em>
  <hr /><a name="officerspennant"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OFFICER�S PENNANTS</dt>
  <dd>The term that may be used to describe those pennants (often - but not exclusively - a 
  swallow-tailed version of the relevant club burgee or flag) flown by the past or present 
  officers of a club, especially of a yacht or boating club � a flag officer, yacht officer 
  or officer&rsquo;s broad pennant or a yacht officer&rsquo;s pennant �  but see 
  &lsquo;<a href="#officersflags">officer's flags</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb7.html#broadpennant">broad pennant 3)</a>&rsquo; (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb8.html#burgee">burgee</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs9.html#swallowtail">swallow-tail(ed)</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d166b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d166b.gif" alt="[officer's pennant]" border="0" height="108" /></a> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d166c.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d166c.gif" alt="[officer's pennant]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br />
  <em> Yacht Commodore and Vice-Commodore,
  </em> 
  <a href="ie~nyc.html#officer"><em>National Yacht Club</em></a><em>, Ireland 
  (fotw)    
   </em></dd>
 
  <hr /><a name="officialflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OFFICIAL FLAG</dt>
  <dd>1) A flag that has been formally adopted by the relevant authority, and/or is considered by them to 
  represent a particular entity, institution or cause, as opposed to a design or type which is not so authorized 
  - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-u.html#unofficialflag">unofficial flag</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-d.html#dejure">de jure</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf2.html#flaglaw">flag law</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi4.html#institutionalflagofficial">institutional flags (official)</a>&rsquo;, and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt6.html#typeflag">type flag</a>&rsquo;).</dd> 
  <dd>2) A term that may be employed to describe a sub-national flag which is specifically for official rather 
  then general civil use, and usually distinguished by the addition of arms (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvba.html">banner 4)</a>&lsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvci.html#civicflag">civil flag</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc2.html#ceremonialflag">ceremonial flag 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs7.html#stateserviceflag">state service flag</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs8.html#subnationalflag">sub-national flag</a>&rsquo; with following notes).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2357.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2357.gif" alt="[Hapoel Tel-Aviv official flag]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2358.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2358.gif" alt="[Hapoel Tel-Aviv unofficial flag]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4391.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4391.gif" alt="[Hesse official flag]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>Official and Unofficial Flag of the <a href="il@hapta.html">Hapoel Tel-Aviv</a> Football Club, Israel (fotw);
  Official Flag/Ensign of <a href="de-he.html">Hesse</a>, Germany (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="ogival"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OGIVAL</dt>
  <dd>The term for a form of flag (now obsolete), or of a gonfanon, where the 
  fly is rounded and comes to a point &ndash; boat-tailed or shield-shaped &ndash; but see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#lanceolate">lanceolate</a>&rsquo; (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve1.html#engrailedfly">engrailed fly</a>&rsquo;, 
  <a href="vxt-dvg2.html#gonfalon">gonfalon 1)</a>,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg2.html#gothicshield">Gothic shield</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs3.html#shield">shield</a>&rsquo;).
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d301.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d301.gif" alt="Persia, 14th century" border="0" width="159" height="106" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d301b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d301b.gif" alt="Grenada, Spain c1350" border="0" width="169" height="105" /></a>&nbsp;
  <br /><span class="style2"><em>Flag of <a href="ir_f0fxx.html">Persia</a> 
  c1350? (fotw); Flag of <a href="es-gr_14.html">Granada</a>, Spain c1350 (fotw)
  </em>
  <p><em>Please note that the differences between &ldquo;ogival&rdquo; and &ldquo;lanceolate&rdquo; are 
  often very slight, and we suggest that both entries be consulted.</em></dd>
  <hr /><a name="oldglory"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OLD GLORY</dt>
  <dd>1) Generally a poetic nickname for the US national flag &ndash; the Stars and Stripes (see 
  also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb5.html#betsyrossflag">Betsy Ross flag</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc7.html#continentalcolors">continental colours</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#eaglestandard">eagle standard</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf8.html#franklinflag">Franklin flag</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg4.html#greatstarflags">great star flags</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-q.html#quincunx">quincunx</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#starspangledbanner">star-spangled banner</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#starsandstripes">stars and stripes</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>2) Specifically referring to a US national flag bearing 34 stars and a small white anchor, 
  reputedly belonging to a Captain William Driver.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d510.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d510.gif" alt="old glory" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d228.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d228.gif" alt="old glory" border="0" height="108" /></a><br>
  <em>National Flag of the <a href="us.html">United States</a> (fotw); <a href="us-glor.html">Captain Driver&rsquo;s Flag</a> (fotw)</em></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="oneandahalfarmedcross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">ONE-AND-A-HALF ARMED CROSS</dt>
  <dd>The term used in Eastern European heraldry &ndash; and a direct translation of the Polish P&oacute;ltora krzyz &ndash; that 
  describes a Latin cross which has a second horizontal arm projecting on one side only - usually the sinister 
  (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#cross">cross 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcs.html#crosslorraine">cross of Lorraine</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#latincross">Latin cross</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt6.html#twoandahalfarmedcross">two-and-a-half armed cross</a>&rsquo;).  
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4820.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4820.gif" alt="Arms - Siemiatycze. Poland" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d839d.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d839d.gif" alt="Arms - Kobylin-Borzymy, Poland" border="0" height="108"  /></a>
    <a href="../images/v/vxt-d839c.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d839c.gif" alt="Flag - Siemiatycze. Poland" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br />
  <em>Flag and Arms of <a href="pl-pd-kb.html">Kobylin-Borzymy</a>, Poland (fotw);
  Flag of <a href="pl-pd-st.html">Siemiatycze</a>. Poland (fotw); 
  </em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="onomast"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">ONOMAST </dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-n.html#namepennant">name pennant</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d443.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d443.gif" alt="onomast" border="0" width="393" height="54" /></a><br /><em>Onomast/Name Pennant of the Schooner Walter Holly, New Brunswick c1890 (fotw)  </em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="open"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OPEN </dt>
  <dd>In some (particularly South European) heraldic usage, a term used when the field can see seen through the door and/or windows of a fortified 
  or similar building � but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva1.html#ajoure">ajour&#233;</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf1.html#field">field 2)</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4393.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4393.gif" alt="open example" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4821.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4821.gif" alt="open example" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4394.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4394.gif" alt="open example" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="es-gi-pq.html">Porqueres</a>, Spain (fotw);
  Flag of <a href="si-107.html">Rogatec</a>, Slovenia (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="pt-brb.html">Borba</a>, Portugal (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="opencrown"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OPEN CROWN </dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc8.html#coronet">coronet</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <span class="style2">
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4822.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4822.gif" alt="open crown example" border="0" height="108" /></a></span><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="es-ic-gm.html">La Gomera</a>, Spain (fotw) </em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="openlozenge"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OPEN LOZENGE </dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvv2.html#voidedlozenge">voided lozenge</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d394a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d394a.gif" alt="Voided lozenge - Morlanwelz" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="be-whtmw.html">Morlanwelz</a>, Belgium (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
    
  <hr /><a name="opensleeve"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OPEN SLEEVE </dt>
  <dd>A technical term for the normal sleeve of a flag that is open at both ends to receive a staff or 
  hoistline - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs4.html#sleeve">sleeve 2)</a>&rsquo; (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc4.html#closedsleeve">closed sleeve</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh2.html#heading">heading</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh4.html#hoistedflag">hoisting</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="opticalproportions"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">OPTICAL PROPORTIONS</dt>
  <dd>1) A term used when the relative dimensions of a series of stripes progressively 
  widen between the hoist and the fly in order to appear even when the flag is flying<span class="style2"> 
  �</span> graduated stripes � an example would be the national ensign of France
  (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvch.html#charge">charge 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh4.html#hoist">hoist</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf5.html#fly">fly</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="#offsettowards">off-set towards</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp8.html#proportions">proportions 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvsb.html#stripe">stripe</a>&rsquo; and
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvv2.html#visualcenter">visual centre</a>&rsquo;).<br>
  2) A term also used when a charge is set slightly towards the hoist so that it appears to be centred under the same circumstances<span class="style2"> 
  � </span>as in the federal service flag of Germany. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d329e.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d329e.gif" alt="France" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d539a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d539a.gif" alt="German federal service flag" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br />
  <span class="style2"><em>National Ensign of <a href="fr.html#ens">France</a> (fotw); Federal Service Flag of 
  <a href="de_state.html">Germany</a> (fotw)</em> 
  </span> </p></dd></dl>
